            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the alcohol calorie calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates how many calories you get from the alcohol
                in your drinks. It focuses on
                <strong>pure alcohol calories</strong> (ethanol), which are the
                same whether they come from beer, wine or spirits. Sugars,
                juices and mixers can add extra calories that are not fully
                captured unless you include them in the “extra calories” field.
              </p>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Volume of pure alcohol</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( V_{\text{alcohol}} = V_{\text{drink}} \times
                  \frac{\text{ABV}}{100} \)
                </p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( V_{\text{drink}} \) = volume of the drink (mL or fl oz)
                  </li>
                  <li>ABV = alcohol by volume (%)</li>
                </ul>
                <hr class="my-2" />
                <p><strong>2. Grams of alcohol</strong></p>
                <p>Ethanol density ≈ 0.789 g/mL</p>
                <p>\( \text{grams} = V_{\text{alcohol (mL)}} \times 0.789 \)</p>
                <hr class="my-2" />
                <p><strong>3. Calories from alcohol</strong></p>
                <p>Alcohol provides ≈ 7 kcal per gram:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Calories} = \text{grams} \times 7 \)</p>
                <hr class="my-2" />
                <p><strong>4. Standard drinks</strong></p>
                <p>
                  A “standard drink” is defined differently by country. We
                  approximate:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>US: 14 g alcohol</li>
                  <li>UK: 8 g alcohol (1 unit)</li>
                  <li>EU (typical): 10 g alcohol</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Standard drinks} = \dfrac{\text{total
                  grams}}{\text{grams per standard drink}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: 330 mL beer at 5% ABV</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Drink volume: 330 mL</li>
                <li>ABV: 5%</li>
                <li>Pure alcohol volume: 330 × 0.05 = 16.5 mL</li>
                <li>Grams of alcohol: 16.5 × 0.789 ≈ 13.0 g</li>
                <li>
                  Calories from alcohol: 13.0 × 7 ≈ <strong>91 kcal</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Real beers often contain a bit more due to residual
                carbohydrates, so labels may show 120–150 kcal per bottle.
              </p>

