              <h2>Why alcohol calories matter for weight and health</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>High energy density:</strong> 7 kcal/g is close to fat
                  (9 kcal/g).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Low satiety:</strong> liquid calories are less filling
                  than solid food.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Metabolic priority:</strong> your body burns alcohol
                  first, temporarily slowing fat burning.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hidden sugars:</strong> many drinks contain added
                  sugar, syrups or juices.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Occasional moderate drinking can fit into a balanced lifestyle,
                but regular high intake makes weight control and metabolic
                health more difficult.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips to reduce alcohol calories</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Choose <strong>smaller servings</strong> (e.g. 125 mL wine
                  instead of 175–250 mL).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Prefer <strong>dry wines and light beers</strong> over sweet
                  cocktails and liqueurs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>calorie-free mixers</strong> (soda water, diet
                  mixers) instead of sugary sodas or juices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Alternate each alcoholic drink with a
                  <strong>glass of water</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plan alcohol into your
                  <strong>daily calorie budget</strong> instead of treating it
                  as “extra”.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Medical and safety note</h2>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                This calculator is for informational and educational purposes
                only and does not replace professional medical advice. If you
                are pregnant, taking medications, have liver disease, or have a
                history of addiction, talk to your doctor about whether it is
                safe to drink alcohol. Many national guidelines recommend
                limiting both the <strong>amount</strong> of alcohol and the
                number of <strong>drinking days per week</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How many calories are in a gram of alcohol?</h3>
              <p>
                Pure alcohol provides about
                <strong>7 kilocalories per gram</strong>. This is almost as much
                as fat (9 kcal/g) and significantly more than carbohydrates or
                protein (4 kcal/g).
              </p>

              <h3>Does “zero sugar” mean zero calories?</h3>
              <p>
                No. A drink can be sugar-free but still contain alcohol, which
                has calories. A shot of vodka with soda water has no sugar but
                still around 90–100 kcal from alcohol.
              </p>

              <h3>Is wine better than beer for weight control?</h3>
              <p>
                Per <em>standard drink</em>, beer and wine are often similar in
                calories. The difference usually comes from serving size and how
                fast you drink them. A large pint of strong beer can easily
                exceed the calories of a small glass of wine.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for non-alcoholic beer or wine?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but set ABV close to 0%. The calculator will then show
                almost zero alcohol calories. Keep in mind that non-alcoholic
                drinks may still contain some sugar, which you can approximate
                using the “extra calories” field if you know it.
              </p>

              <h3>How accurate are these estimates?</h3>
              <p>
                The formulas are standard and robust, but real-world values
                depend on the exact brand, recipe and serving size. For precise
                information, always check the nutrition label or producer data
                when available.
              </p>
